        [
            {
                "id": "925184340005122128",
                "type": 0,
                "content": "I think the main benefit would be cutting down on duplication of logic by just reusing the Anchor Rust client code.\n\nI think creating transactions is the part where this could be useful.\n\nI don\u2019t want to use Rust for sending network requests as making that play nice with asyncio is a can of worms last I checked. I also don\u2019t think there\u2019s much point using Rust for IDL parsing as it wouldn\u2019t save much code (if any).\n\nThere\u2019s still quite a bit of duplication involved in wrapping a crate for Python as you can see in this post https://users.rust-lang.org/t/wrap-rust-library-for-python-without-changing-rust-library/69285",
                "channel_id": "925180358025150534",
                "author": {
                    "id": "856894333180706876",
                    "username": "LegalizeOnionFutures",
                    "avatar": "6818b2cfdac0afa900ebd98f946a81cc",
                    "discriminator": "1698",
                    "public_flags": 0
                },
                "attachments": [],
                "embeds": [
                    {
                        "type": "article",
                        "url": "https://users.rust-lang.org/t/wrap-rust-library-for-python-without-changing-rust-library/69285",
                        "title": "Wrap Rust Library for Python (without changing Rust library)",
                        "description": "Coming from C++ I would implement my C++ library (classes, structs, functions) in pure C++ and as a second step I would use pybind11 to wrap them so that they can be used in Python. For example:  // Vector3.hpp struct Vector3 {     Vector3(int x, int y, int z)         : x(x), y(y), z(z) { }      double length() const {         return std::sqrt(x...",
                        "color": 16777215,
                        "provider": {
                            "name": "The Rust Programming Language Forum"
                        }
                    }
